api.github.com/repos/matplotlib/matplotlib/milestones/84/labels","id":9767087,"node_id":"MI_kwDOABUios4AlQiv","number":84,"title":"v3.10.0","description":"New features and API changes","creator":{"login":"ksunden","id":2501846,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjI1MDE4NDY=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/2501846?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/ksunden","html_url":"https://github.com/ksunden","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ksunden/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ksunden/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ksunden/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ksunden/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ksunden/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ksunden/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ksunden/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ksunden/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/ksunden/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"open_issues":75,"closed_issues":190,"state":"open","created_at":"2023-08-09T22:35:22Z","updated_at":"2024-09-13T12:11:30Z","due_on":null,"closed_at":null},"comments":1,"created_at":"2024-03-15T09:26:22Z","updated_at":"2024-09-13T12:11:30Z","closed_at":"2024-09-13T12:11:30Z","author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"### Problem

The matplotlib lib axes_grid1 is a great toolbox for building complex plots (especially for panel of images). The size of the grid is defined through axes divider which are typically list of [Sizes](https://github.com/matplotlib/matplotlib/blob/48c065ec11ce685f31744546a4c07d653576ca3e/lib/mpl_toolkits/axes_grid1/axes_size.py) objects.

Those object support for now only addition and multiplication on the left (e.g `0.5*Size.AxesX(ax)` works, but not `Size.AxesX(ax)*0.5` 
Currently only `__rmul__` and `__add__` are available.


### Proposed solution


Adding more arithmetic dunder methods (like `__mul__`,`__div__`, `__sub__`[^1]) would bring more flexibility and a better UX in designing axes divider grid. 

A proposal of implementation would be the following: 

```python 
# lib/mpl_toolkits/axes_grid1/axes_size.py

class _Base:
    def __rmul__(self, other):
        return Fraction(other, self)

    def __add__(self, other):
        if isinstance(other, _Base):
            return Add(self, other)
        else:
            return Add(self, Fixed(other))

    # new stuff

    def __mul__(self, other):
        return Fraction(self, other)

    def __div__(self, other):
        return Fraction(1/other, self)

    def __sub__(self, other):
        # 
        return Add(self, Fixed(-other)
```

I willy happily submit a PR with this change (and more if required). 





[^1]: Some check may also be enforced (to avoid negative values for instance)
